\newlabel{sec:format}{{3.2}{4}{Binary File Format}{subsection.3.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces The \texttt  {.acon} binary file format. A 116-byte fixed header contains magic bytes, version, entity counts for all 7 entity types, timestamps, and a BLAKE3 checksum over the JSON payload. Entity data is serialized as JSON within the binary envelope, enabling flexible schema evolution.}}{4}{figure.caption.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:fileformat}{{4}{4}{The \texttt {.acon} binary file format. A 116-byte fixed header contains magic bytes, version, entity counts for all 7 entity types, timestamps, and a BLAKE3 checksum over the JSON payload. Entity data is serialized as JSON within the binary envelope, enabling flexible schema evolution}{figure.caption.7}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Governance composition model. An agent action first encounters policy evaluation (most-restrictive-wins). Allow triggers condition and risk limit checks; RequireApproval enters the three-phase approval workflow; Deny records a violation. Approved actions create obligations with deadlines. Risk limit exceedance and policy denials both produce immutable violation records, ensuring a complete audit trail regardless of the decision path.}}{4}{figure.caption.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:composition}{{5}{4}{Governance composition model. An agent action first encounters policy evaluation (most-restrictive-wins). Allow triggers condition and risk limit checks; RequireApproval enters the three-phase approval workflow; Deny records a violation. Approved actions create obligations with deadlines. Risk limit exceedance and policy denials both produce immutable violation records, ensuring a complete audit trail regardless of the decision path}{figure.caption.8}{}}
